at work variously in parallel, in concert, and in resistance to some forms of male power, and contends that only by mapping these networks do we gain a full understanding of the nature of monarchical power. Pick’s focus on the roles, possibilities, and limitations faced by these royal women forces us to reevaluate medieval gender norms and their relationship to power and to rethink the power structures of the era. Well illustrated with images of significant objects, Her Father’s Daughter is marked by Pick’s wide-ranging interdisciplinary approach, which encompasses liturgy, art, manuscripts, architecture, documentary texts, historical narratives, saints’ lives, theological treatises, and epigraphy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMonarchyzSpainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPower (Social sciences)zSpainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSex rolezSpainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aUpper class womenzSpainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomen and religionzSpainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomenzSpainxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106658710 cprintz978150171433740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501714344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501714344/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK